1 relation to mandatory reentry supervision.
2 (7) Subject to subsection (3) of this section, the period of mandatory reentry
3 supervision shall conclude upon completion of the individual's minimum expiration
4 of sentence.
5 (8) If the board issues a warrant for the arrest of an inmate for absconding from
6 supervision during the mandatory reentry supervision period, and the inmate is
7 subsequently returned to prison as a violator of conditions of supervision for
8 absconding, the inmate shall not receive credit toward the remainder of his or her
9 sentence for the time spent absconding.
10 (9) The department shall report the results of the mandatory reentry supervision
11 program to the Legislative Research Commission for referral to the Interim Joint
12 Committee on Judiciary or the Senate and House Standing Committees on
13 Judiciary, as appropriate, by February 1 of each year[, 2015].
14 Section 2. KRS 504.020 is amended to read as follows:
15 (1) A person is not responsible for criminal conduct if at the time of the[such] conduct,
16 as a result of mental illness or intellectual disability, he or she lacks substantial
17 capacity [either ]to appreciate the nature and quality of[criminality of] his or her
18 conduct[ or to conform his conduct to the requirements of law].
19 (2) As used in this chapter, the term "mental illness or intellectual disability" does not
20 include an abnormality manifested only by repeated criminal or otherwise antisocial
21 conduct.
22 (3) A defendant may prove mental illness or intellectual disability, as used in this
23 section, in exculpation of criminal conduct.
24 Section 3. KRS 504.060 is amended to read as follows:
25 As used in this chapter, unless the context otherwise requires:
26 (1) "Department" means the Department of Corrections;
27 (2) "Examiner" means a psychologist or psychiatrist who examines, treats, or reports
Page 3 of 6
HB042220.100 - 1413 - XXXX 4/1/2026 4:20 PM Engrossed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 422/EN
1 on a defendant's mental condition as required by this chapter;
2 (3) "Forensic psychiatric facility" means a mental institution or facility, or part thereof,
3 designated by the secretary for the purpose and function of providing inpatient
4 evaluation, care, and treatment for [mentally ill persons or ]individuals with an
5 intellectual disability or a mental illness who have been charged with or convicted
6 of a felony;
7 (4) "Foreseeable future" means not more than three hundred sixty (360) days;
8 (5) "Incompetency to stand trial" means, as a result of mental condition, lack of
9 capacity to appreciate the nature and consequences of the proceedings against one
10 or to participate rationally in one's own defense;
11 (6) "Individual with an intellectual disability" means an individual with significantly
12 subaverage general intellectual functioning existing concurrently with deficits in
13 adaptive behavior and manifested during the developmental period and is a
14 condition which may exist concurrently with mental illness or insanity;
15 (7) "Insanity" means, as a result of mental illness or intellectual disability[condition],
16 lack of substantial capacity [either ]to appreciate the nature and
17 quality[criminality] of one's conduct[ or to conform one's conduct to the
18 requirements of law];
19 (8) "Mental illness" means substantially impaired capacity to use self-control,
20 judgment, or discretion in the conduct of one's affairs and social relations,
21 associated with maladaptive behavior or recognized emotional symptoms where
22 impaired capacity, maladaptive behavior, or emotional symptoms can be related to
23 physiological, psychological, or social factors;
24 (9) "Psychiatrist" means a physician licensed pursuant to KRS Chapter 311 who is
25 certified or eligible to apply for certification by the American Board of Psychiatry
26 and Neurology, Inc.;
27 (10) "Psychologist" means a person licensed at the doctoral level pursuant to KRS
Page 4 of 6
HB042220.100 - 1413 - XXXX 4/1/2026 4:20 PM Engrossed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 422/EN
1 Chapter 319 who has been designated by the Kentucky Board of Examiners of
2 Psychology as competent to perform examinations;
3 (11) "Secretary" means the secretary of the Cabinet for Health and Family Services;
4 (12) "Treatment":
5 (a) Means medication or counseling, therapy, psychotherapy, and other
6 professional services provided by or at the direction of psychologists or
7 psychiatrists; and[. "Treatment"]
8 (b) Shall not include electroshock therapy or psychosurgery; and
9 (13) "Treatment facility" means an institution or part thereof, approved by the Cabinet
10 for Health and Family Services, which provides evaluation, care, and treatment for
11 insane or [mentally ill persons or ]individuals with an intellectual disability or a
12 mental illness on an inpatient or outpatient basis.
13 Section 4. KRS 504.120 is amended to read as follows:
14 (1) Except as provided in subsection (2) of this section, in cases in which the
15 defendant provides evidence at trial of his or her mental illness or insanity at the
16 time of the offense, the jury or court may find the defendant:
17 (a)[(1)] Guilty;
18 (b)[(2)] Not guilty;
19 (c)[(3)] Not guilty by reason of insanity at the time of the offense; or
20 (d)[(4)] Guilty but mentally ill at the time of the offense.
21 (2) A jury or court shall not return a verdict that finds the defendant:
22 (a) For one (1) count, not guilty by reason of insanity at the time of the offense;
23 and
24 (b) For any other count arising out of a single course of conduct and tried
25 during the same trial, guilty or guilty but mentally ill at the time of the
26 offense.
27 (3) The court shall instruct the jury on the prohibition established in subsection (2)
Page 5 of 6
HB042220.100 - 1413 - XXXX 4/1/2026 4:20 PM Engrossed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 422/EN
1 of this section.
2 Section 5. KRS 504.150 is amended to read as follows:
3 (1) (a) The court shall sentence a defendant found guilty but mentally ill at the time
4 of the offense to the local jail or to the department[ of Corrections] in the
5 same manner as a defendant found guilty.
6 (b) If the defendant is found guilty but mentally ill, treatment shall be provided
7 the defendant until the treating professional determines that the treatment is
8 no longer necessary or until expiration of his or her sentence, whichever
9 occurs first.
10 (c) If the treating professional determines that treatment is still necessary upon
11 expiration of the defendant's sentence, the treating professional or the
12 Commonwealth shall petition the sentencing court for:
13 1. Involuntary hospitalization or admission under KRS Chapter 202A or
14 202B; or
15 2. Court-ordered community-based outpatient treatment under KRS
16 Chapter 202A.
17 (2) Treatment shall be a condition of probation, shock probation, conditional discharge,
18 parole, or conditional release so long as the defendant requires treatment for his or
19 her mental illness in the opinion of his or her treating professional.
20 Section 6. This Act may be cited as Logan's Law.
